@book{Boffa1999,
abstract = {This document reviews the current state of knowledge on agroforestry parkland systems. These systems are generally understood as landscapes in which mature trees occur scattered in cultivated or recently fallowed fields, in which livestock production may be either a significant or secondary component; they are intermediate between savanna woodlands and grasslands in terms of vegetation types. Parkland systems are for many local populations very important for food security, income generation and environmental protection. They are found primarily in the semiarid and subhumid zones of West Africa, but similar systems exist in other such zones and in temperate regions. The document first provides definitions and a thorough description of their distribution and diversity and discusses different ways of classifying them. It also presents data on current trends in parkland development and assesses determining factors. An in-depth analysis is then provided of biophysical tree- soil-crop interactions and the factors regulating them, and various improved parkland management techniques are described. The strength and limitations are then examined of institutional arrangements and the constraints imposed by Sahelian forest policies on the sustainable management of parklands. The production, use and marketing of parkland products is reviewed with an emphasis on their contribution to food security, local and national income as well as social values. Overall costs and benefits of the practice of parkland agroforestry are evaluated. In conclusion, the document identifies crucial research needs and promising avenues for promoting sustainable management of parkland systems},
